segments.text: University of North Texas and Texas A&M has reached out a lot.
Now, UT has a center that does a lot of research, and they're going out and working with schools and those kind of things.
I don't think that they've really had that serious commitment, and I think they've probably missed the opportunity as well.
See, we've got too many doctors.
I'm sorry they don't have the academic courses
to really make the intellectual, academic side of the doctoral program what it ought to be.
But they're more field-based, perhaps.
I'd recommend four, probably.
Four.
Now, the fourth one may be a combination, say, that may be partially online, that may be really for the practitioner,
It could be a combination, perhaps, of Stephen Foster, Sam Houston State.
And I would like to see a systems doctor at Texas A&M University, a systems doctor.
And I would recommend the same thing to the University of Texas system.
Have a systems doctor so that they're related to the affiliated institution.
You know, we talk about not having enough academic courses, but probably each one of those institutions has one or two people who are as good as the ones at Texas A&M University.

So if you really could do some imaginative work, and I talked about this earlier with our former chancellor, who has a PhD in education, I think, about assistance doctrine, and it did make some of my colleagues very happy.
I organized a meeting with all professors in the A&M system in Austin about three years ago, and we proposed the idea there, and it wasn't very popular because
Oh, he thought he was super, I guess.
Barry Thompson?
Oh, yeah.
And Bill Reed does as well.
But it was just that idea that we're taking the scholarship away from the institutions when in fact we wouldn't be.
We would have the making accessible and the assisting doctors, and they would have the best of the best.
from each institution and also be able to provide very rich internship mentoring programs for young superintendents and principals doing that.
That may not come about.
I think one of the big
A couple of us really had a great idea, I thought, to have a course on the history development of American education as being a cornerstone to the strength of America.
And having a course that was really interdisciplinary taught by some of the really exciting teachers on campus and have that centered in the College of Education
And it's absolutely critical to the future of our country.
Well, I put together some ideas.
Jack Campbell, who was in philosophy at that time, and a couple others were excited about it.
But you know, when we got right down to it, the College of Education said, who's going to teach?
Where are the resources?
If we get it passed, what are we going to do about it?
And then, of course, there was some of the other friction.
I believe we have to force them to have education as a discipline, taught.
And that was a missed opportunity.
I really believe it.
Most students who go into engineering or even liberal arts or whatever have no clue about the structure of American education, how it's funded, and how important it is to our society.
Almost 95% of them.
So that was a missed opportunity.
And that was just another dream I had, I guess.
The first women I remember were taking courses in summer before women were admitted to the institution.
But when I was working on my PhD, I was almost finished in 67.
And in fact, I was going through some stuff.
And we were spelling mother and dad's house the other day and parceling out things.
I found a memo signed by Haskell Monroe.
approving my acceptance of candidacy, providing I take another course or two or finish my dissertation, those kinds of things.
At that time, I remember the first woman coming into the graduate program, and that would have been about 1967.
Prior to that, I can't remember a woman in the graduate program
When we went from the Department of Education and Psychology in the College of Liberal Arts to the College of Education in 1969, then women started coming in in smaller numbers.
So out of the first 50 doctors, I guess I'd have to look across that list.
I'd say probably six of them, seven of them are women.
I really don't, but there were so few of them.
It was difficult to say.
I remember one woman named Blum was a very bright, very good student, and I remember she blended in very well with most of the males.
And now, of course, about half of our students in administration are women.
And now that we've combined the Department of Administration and Human Resource Development, it may be 60%.
Well, there was, in terms of looking at the first women on this faculty in administration, they had women in teacher education faculty before administration faculty.
I'm trying to think who the first woman would have been, unless it's probably the model agent, perhaps, about...
about seven or eight years ago, I guess.
And I can't remember a woman faculty, and I can remember adjuncts, so people coming in to teach courses, but full-time, I think, Dr. Lincoln.
Now we have two African-American women.
We have two, three women.
three Anglo women, and that's out of a full-time faculty of about 10 people.
So we really made some difference there in terms of color and gender in our department.
I feel really good about that, and I think all of us do.
It's been like the nation in terms of staffing schools.
I think the men dominate the secondary level in the principalships, and the women.
There's far more men teaching secondary level and junior high level than you find at the elementary level.
Most of the principals at the elementary level are women, when 40 years ago they were men.
So women are coming in through the elementary level, taking assistant superintendents, and then become superintendents, because even though the secondary principal is the
gateway to the superintendency.

Most of those positions still held by men, but since there's a great concern now about who's going to fill those apprenticeships, we know some of our women are doing a great job, and just as tough as the guys, and many times understand curriculum better than the guys because we've been at the elementary level.
Now, in terms of the accountability issues in the state, us in North Carolina are considered to have the best accountability system in the nation.
Because of our concern, I guess, going back to early legislation in the 1980s, when Governor White was here, we started right then with testing, with tabs, teams, to toss tests.
And so where we've made great strides, I think, in terms of student achievement,
We also make great strides with numbers of kids taking ACP and SAT.
We have 53% of Texans now taking the ACP, SAT.
When 15 years ago, there might have been 30% taking it.
And as you well know, as a college president and professor, the more people taking the SAT, ACP, you've got a pretty good chance of the grades leveling off or certainly even dipping.
Mm-hmm.
Well, there's no question about it.
I think that his vision for education and the kinds of legislation that came about during this time set the stage for improving schools.
We had a real problem, I think, when the parole commission came along about seven or eight years ago that Dean Torrigan served on.
Corrigan was the only bright light on that committee, and they removed education and discipline from the colleges, thinking that there was no academic content there.
And now we have a real problem preparing teachers with a few numbers of education.
That's another missed opportunity.
I think we have this university and other universities fighting that kind of mentality that all teaching is content-driven.
And Corrigan was the only bright light, but we lost that battle.
And so it's been difficult.
We can't major in the health and kinesiology here.
I mean, we can't major in the physical education here.
Major in any major in health and kinesiology or interdisciplinary studies.
Now, at the graduate level, you can, education administration.
So that was a missed opportunity, I think, in the state.
I think probably, I can't remember
I know some of them at that time were out in Bowen, head of the State Board of Education.
I'm trying to think of his name.
He's been deceased for a while.
Frank Hubert, they were advising.
So we had some really solid people advising White, but I think he said,
that were not bright lights, or as they say, not the sharpest knife in the door.
And where Bush has come on, and George Bush has come on and gotten a lot of credit, to his credit, he did appoint a top person for the Commission of Education, Mike Moses, who's now 11th.
And he had put the right things in motion with the governor's support to really help the governor, I think, get the name, get at least the brand of being an education governor.
And I want to give him some credit for that.
But he knew how to appoint the right person to get things going.
And now he's appointed Jim Nelson, who's his friend, a lawyer, and he's doing a good job.
But obviously he doesn't have the respect that the superintendent gave to Mike Moses.
And I've got November I'll have Jim Nelson coming here for the second year in a row through our conference with the superintendent.
He's gaining more favor because he's real positive about things.
Uh-huh.
Not particularly.
Certainly Connolly, White, and I think Bush as well.
Oh, I think probably our SMU, Bill Clements.
would get a low mark, even though he kind of took the governorship.
Smith, I think, low mark.
Because they just didn't have a vision for education.
Yeah.
Started here, it was really tough.
I was recruited to come here.
I really didn't apply officially.
And the opportunity to come back home, and the first thing out of the bat, I wound up with a very huge U.S. Department of Education grant that Jim McNamara had authored.
But I wound up being an essential investigator on it the first year.
I wound up also planning...
the Administrative Leadership Institute, teaching full class load, and took on several doctoral students immediately.
And it was pretty heavy.
Then, as time went on, I was able to, I think, get myself a little more organized.
But as I did that, I became more and more involved at the national level.
Early 80s, I spent time watching BC away from campus.
We took a sabbatical and was in Europe in 85-86 to try to ease the pain.
In 1985, I'd been here about 10 years, and I was exhausted.
I mean, I'd lost my zeal for teaching.
I had an opportunity to go to the University of Virginia.
They wanted me to come.
They had a chair there.
They were interested in me taking it.
And...
And all of a sudden, Boston University called.
I had talked to them one summer.
I called a global workshop in the Mediterranean for them.
And they called and said, we would like you to go to Europe for a year for us and be our guest professor.
And that was a godsend.
I left for a full year.
They covered me here.
Boston picked up all my benefits and salaries.
When I got back from that, my whole life took on a different meaning.
I was more excited, more intellectually challenged.
And that's when I started, I think, really becoming more productive as a writer, as a speaker, as a teacher.
And since that time, I've been involved with the study abroad program, so I can go to Europe occasionally and get abroad when I get so steamed.
Because I'm either writing on a book or doing research papers or speaking.
My life has changed in terms of when I wrote this little book on the study of the future.
This was a 1995 publication.
All of a sudden, my speaking opportunities became much, much greater, at least assignments.
And I think the more and more I taught and the more I spoke and the more I wrote, the more my life has become much busier.
But I've learned to deal with it better.
I'm doing too much all the time, but I've learned to deal with it better.
I'm not happy unless I'm just hell-mell now into writing and speaking and those kind of things.
So I moved very quickly from full professorship, and then a couple of times people talked with me about taking deanship, but I just didn't leave.
And now most of the things I do I really enjoy doing, even though I've taken on too many assignments.
here and across the nation.
But thank God for that year in Europe.
And we don't have enough sabbaticals at this university.
We have developmental leave now, more opportunities maybe in our department than we've ever had.
And that's a good sign.
But I served on the developmental leave committee here several years.
And you had to absolutely snow everybody.
You had to have the most brilliant thing.
You had all these caveats.
You couldn't be writing a book.
You couldn't do this.
You couldn't do that.
You had to actually be going.
If you're going somewhere, you couldn't be going somewhere to write a book.
That was not academic.
And so it was almost tough to get us back.
It was almost impossible around here.
Now the opportunity has come.
I had to make my own break to go to Washington for four months.
And I worked with Dr. Corrigan.
He told me to write a draft on how I could cover myself while I was gone.
He helped me do that.
The year in Europe, they hired somebody to teach my classes.
But I had to lay it out and show them how we could do that.
This college was not used to anybody taking developmental leave.
And I think, truly, I was one of the first people to say, I've got to get out of here.
I've got to repress because I'm involved in too many things.
Speaking, writing, teaching, committees on campus, athletic council, church work, board presence, the kind of things that busy, crazy people do.
So thank God for that sabbatical, and then the study abroad and the European experiences here have really helped me.
I've been pretty fortunate there.
I've talked about...
four, maybe five courses since I've been here.
Three of them I have taught, the same three I have taught for the last 10 years.
I'm teaching the course called The Nature and Problems of Administrative Behavior, which is our top doctoral leadership organizational dynamics behavior course.
I'm teaching a course on program evaluation, which is now, I have adopted it to the state

academic indicator system, accountability system, so that we go online and really look at data of all the school systems to see how well they're doing on the top stats, on attendance, the criteria to determine whether you're exemplary, recognized, acceptable, or not.
I'll have to change the shift there, but that's a great course primarily for K-12 teachers who want to be a part of this.
The third course is the Educational Planning Futurism course,
which I brought here in 75, and it is truly an interdisciplinary course.
I taught it yesterday.
I've got students in engineering, business, and education, and that's an exciting course because we look at broad futures.
Education is only part of that, but those are three courses that I really, really, really treasure.
Okay?

All right, the first course, the administrative behavior courses, are primarily our PhD students who are, they take that, try to take that during the earliest part of their doctoral program because it is the, and I think my colleagues will agree, it's the heartbeat of our discipline.
It is the terminology, it is the theory of basics, where we come from.

and how we're trying to develop more of a respect in terms of our research and our development arm there, in terms of who we are as an organization, drawing on all kinds of organizational theory and literature.

Next course, the program evaluation class, mostly master students who are principals, who are working for a principal certification, or who are classroom teachers, who want to understand accountability, because I spend a lot of time on teacher groups, teaching cycles, how to evaluate students,
And in the third course, I've got two entrepreneurs in there who are not working on PhDs, who've been in the business world.
I've got a retired professor from mechanical engineering who's just sitting in on the class.
I've got seven or eight in ag development, international development.
I've got an educational psychologist.
I've got about 12.
five or six, I guess, who are in higher education one way or another.
Most of them are at the doctoral level.
Some are at the master's level.
Yes, in the theory class, they have two exams.
I guess my midterm exam is known as the, it's the most feared exam in this department from all I can hear.
But all it is, I just make sure they know the terminology, know the literature, they know the names, they know the systems thought that's come over the years.
And then they have a final exam in that course.
They have a term paper on some theories and or theory.
They have critiques.
They must read and turn in critiques that are readings that are found in the syllabus
or elsewhere that's tied to that direct topic.
They've got to have something read and turned in before we start a new topic.
Then they're assigned a consistent professorship, where they actually draw on the hat and pull out a reading.
And if they don't understand what that person's written, you have to call them, get in touch with them.
They've got to share with me.
Tonight I'm talking about leadership for him.
They've got to talk about what, say, Harlan Cleveland might have talked about, what he might have said.
The other class, the program evaluations class, I put them in groups of four.
They, then, can select any school system in the state of Texas.

They've got to, I mean, they've got to look at, they've got to go online, they've got to get a tremendous understanding of that school district in terms of its wealth, its demographics, its test scores, its dropouts, its faculty, how well educated they are, superintendent, how long they've been there, board members, everything about them.
And they've got to report.
Why do they think that district's doing better than it should, or why it's not doing as well as it should?
And then each of those committee members have to do one of the campuses and describe it very well.
My goal is they've got to know more about accountability when they go back at the end of that course and their principal, or after superintendent.
Third course, the future class, and it's exciting.
I put them into teams of, I've got 22 students.
I've got teams of five.
They've got to create a community.
through the year 2020, like Hoyleville there, city limits population 50,000, and they'll present that.

I have been Don Sweeney from Urban Planning, and they've got to present a city through the year 2020 that has everything, their food, their transportation, their medicine, their religious centers, their recreation, all about that.
and explained to us, and they win a prize.
That one team that wins gets a prize, and the prizes are made in my garage.
I won't tell you what they are, because it's a fantastic prize.
They look terrible, but the kids love them.
The students love them.
Then the other project, each of them has to write a personal scenario.
Ten years in future.
They can't be failures.
They've got to be successful.
They've got to say what they're doing, how well they're doing it, how they're getting to where they're doing it, how they're using information.
And they've got to tell us how they got there from this point.
And those are the major assignments in the future class.
And it's really, I run into people all the time 15 years later that reach in their pocket and pull out a little clear marble that I've given them in this class.
I've done it for 20 years.
And they've got to carry that everywhere they go.
Because I say, once you run into problems in your life, I want you to think about what you've learned, use the good intellect you have,
Put the crows and toms down on your decision.
Get that little crystal ball out.
Look into it and make your decision.
And that's been a real joy, a labor of love, that class over the years to see what's happened to people.
Because every once in a while, Kay and you or someone will say, what's your track record in terms of people writing scenarios?
I said, it's scary.
It's phenomenal how they follow those scenarios.
Because it's the first time in most of their careers
They've never had to write down specific goals of where they're going in their life.
So those are the three things.
Most of them are out in the real world or are working on this campus.
Now, some of them come right out of the bachelor's into the master's.
We discourage that unless they're going into student affairs work.
So I'll have some SAHI or student affairs people send.
Generally they're from Texas, but we are now more and more getting people coming in from out of state for our program.
We have built kind of a reputation through our department.
We've got some obviously internationally known people in our department, so we're beginning to attract people from out of state.
We occasionally will attract one or two from Taiwan.
Often we've had two from Russia who come here, and so we're beginning more and more to see.
And we have Chinese visiting scholars, and we've had two or three students from China in the last two or three years.
So that's beginning to happen more and more.
Not many from Mexico, even though we have an agreement to know.
I don't think they're any more rigorous.
I think probably the creative side of it is probably stressed more in terms of thinking out of the box and thinking about what could be.
Because I can remember the early PhD program, we had eight areas we were responsible for in education.
And we had to try to master all eight of those areas in our written exams and everything else.
And in many ways, of course, we had to take two languages in.
Now we take statistics and measurements.
Perhaps part of that was a waste.
It was certainly a mental discipline.
But I really believe that the rigor really has not changed.
The technology has certainly changed a bit.
And I'm experiencing that right now with our new APDGN system.
And finding some limitations in that, knowing full well that eventually it's going to be a benefit.
I guess it's really close between the organizational behavior, especially the motivation leadership elements, and the futures class with the vision element, which is motivational.
So those two courses, I have difficulty deciding between those two because I go into both those classes each night excited, pumped up,
I try to get well prepared.
I tell them that when they walk into that class, they better be ready, because I'm going to be ready.
So those two I really enjoy.
The third one, I don't have to really ramp up so much, because they go online.
The first two or three nights, we've got to get them set the stage.
But I think the leadership, motivation, organizational behavior, and the visioning and futuring are my favorite classes.
I get here sometime between 8 and 9, depends on the day, and stay until 6, 6.30.
But often, spring semester, I have two night classes that go from 5 to 8.
So that's about nine to eight days, usually.
And I work out during the noon hour.
I get an hour and a half break with the long days.
But I guess it's a rare day that I'm here under seven hours, most all that time, unless I'm in a doctoral committee meeting.
And those happen about, on the average, twice a week during the fall and spring semester.
I'm chairing probably right now six to seven dissertations in the writing stage.
I chair about 31 committees.
And I sit on probably about 30 more, and working with five or six master's students in their degree.
So while I'm not at the office, I'll probably be watching TV or eat often with this patient in my lap.
And most of my trips on the plane, heading for speaking somewhere,
I'll carry dissertations with me and proposals.
And that helps a lot.
Usually when I go give a speech somewhere, I grab stuff in my lap and prepare it in the plane.
I'm a jogger, a runner.
I go to the rec center about five days a week and run and lift.
We've got the good knowledge equipment, those kinds of things.
I've got a lake home out at Kent Creek Lake.
And that's been the state sort of place where we can go and just kind of forget things for a while.
Travel.
Carol and I love to travel.
And I can be in Italy one day and things start drifting away.
After the third day, I forget I'm even a professor there, even though I'm teaching undergraduates over there.
So I have to fill those things in because it's just relentless, absolutely relentless in terms of something to do every day.
Yeah.
Yeah.
